's J- and H-band magnitudes are compatible with masses of\na few M$_\\mathrm{Jup}$. However, K-, L- and I-band data draw this conclusion\ninto question. We explore with radiative transfer modeling whether an\nunresolved circum-companion disk can be responsible for the high polarization\nand complex photometry. We find that the set of observations is best explained\nby a heavily extincted low mass ($\\sim 20 \\mathrm{M}_\\mathrm{Jup}$) brown dwarf\nor high mass planet with an unresolved disk and dust envelope.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 6 May 2018 18:34:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-22"}
