{"id":"1805.02370","submitter":"Ling Lin","authors":"Ling Lin, Yongguan Ke, Chunshan He, Chaohong Lee","title":"Hybrid atom-molecule quantum walks in one-dimensional optical lattice","comments":"11 pages, 10 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 98, 043628 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.98.043628","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study hybrid atom-molecule quantum walks in one-dimensional optical\nlattices with two interacting bosonic atoms which may be converted into a\nmolecule. The hybrid atom-molecule energy bands include a continuum band and\ntwo isolated bands, which respectively correspond to scattering states and\ndressed bound states (DBS's). Because of the atom-molecule coupling, the DBS's\nmay appear even in the absence of atom-atom interaction. From an initial state\nof two atoms occupying the same site, in addition to independent quantum walks\nwhich correspond to scattering states, correlated quantum walks appear as a\nsignature of DBS's. Even if the atom-atom interaction and the atom-molecule\ncoupling are much stronger than the tunneling strengths, independent quantum\nwalks may still appear under certain resonant conditions. The correlated\nquantum walks show two light-cones with different propagation velocities, which\ncan be analytically explained by the effective tunneling strengths of the two\ndifferent DBS's. Furthermore, the effective nearest-neighbor tunneling of DBS's\ncan be suppressed to zero, which can be explained by the destructive\ninterference between the atomic pair and the molecule.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 May 2018 07:03:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 8 Aug 2018 09:39:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-11-07"}
